&gt; But concatenative programming is not perfect either. As shown in _Why Concatenative Programming Matters_, a simple expression `f(x, y, z) = x^2 + y^2 - abs(y)` becomes
&gt;
&gt; `drop dup dup × swap abs rot3 dup × swap − +`
&gt;
&gt; But why can't you just write `drop dup (^2) + (^2) - abs` instead?

Do you have any sense of how that last program can be anywhere near correct?
